                <h2 class="page-header">The Necessity of Building a Sustainable Economy</h2>
                <p><strong>Michael Porter – University Professor at Harvard Business School- TED</strong>
Leading authority on the subject of modern competitive strategy for business, he now considers the intersection between society and corporate interests. In his Ted talk, Porter states that it is necessary that companies begin to take the lead in reconceiving the intersection between society and corporate interests. He suggests a solution, that of "shared value," which involves creating economic value in order to also create value for society. 
                    <a href="http://hbr.org/2011/01/the-big-idea-creating-shared-value">Read More</a> </p>
 

<p><strong>Matthieu Ricard – Monk – Davos</strong>
World renowned Buddhist monk Matthieu Ricard, sometimes called “the happiest man on earth” defends values of altruism and compassion. At the World Economic Forum in Davos, he supported that altruism is a necessity in order to run more sustainable corporations.  
</p>

<p>For more reading, please visit our <a href="#">interactive blog</a> where updates on similar subjects are posted.</p>
